<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06258019 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06258019 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Noriega  </CAPTION><LEADPARA>  A jury was selected Friday in Miami for the drug and racketeering trial ofdeposed Panamanian leader Manuel Noriega after both sides narrowed down thefield of potential jurors. &quot;You have now embarked on a very importantproject,&quot; U.S. District Judge William Hoeveler told the 12 jurors and sixalternates chosen from among 180 candidates. The prosecution was to give itsopening statement and call its first witness Monday, the judge said. Noriegaattorney Jon May said the defense won't present its opening statement untilthe prosecution rests, which could be several months. In a trial-relateddevelopment Friday, Diane Cossin, a spokeswoman for the Miami U.S. attorney'soffice, confirmed a published report that the U.S. government had made a dealwith Carlos Lehder, the Colombian drug king serving a life sentence in afederal prison in Illinois, to testify against Noriega. Cossin said thedefense was formally notified of the deal Friday. New York Newsday on Fridayquoted sources it didn't name who said the government might ease up onLehder's life-plus-135-years term in return for testimony that would outlinethe Medellin cartel's connections with Noriega.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  JURORS, ALTERNATES SET FOR NORIEGA TRIAL  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  National News in Brief  </MEMO><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910914  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Saturday  </DAY><MONTH>  September  </MONTH><PG.COL>  6A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  197  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Saturday, September 14, 199100258019,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LAN